#### Economic Resources: Beneath the Surface

The geological wealth of Baffin Island is significant, though often challenging to access. The [Hall Peninsula](/Hall_Peninsula) in the south is part of the [Chidliak Kimberlite Province](/Chidliak_Kimberlite_Province), a region known for its [diamond](/Diamond)-bearing [kimberlite pipes](/Volcanic_pipe). More presently, the [Mary River iron ore mine](/Mary_River_Mine), operational since 2015, represents a substantial economic undertaking, shipping millions of tonnes of ore annually.

#### In Popular Culture: A Dramatic Backdrop

Baffin Island’s stark beauty has not gone unnoticed by the world of cinema. The 1974 film [The White Dawn](/The_White_Dawn) was both set and filmed on the island, featuring predominantly [Inuit performers](/Inuit_languages). More famously, the thrilling opening sequence of the 1977 [James Bond film](/List_of_James_Bond_films), [The Spy Who Loved Me](/The_Spy_Who_Loved_Me_(film)), with its iconic cliff jump and ski parachute drop, was filmed at the imposing [Mount Asgard](/Mount_Asgard) in [Auyuittuq National Park](/Auyuittuq_National_Park). For the more adventurous, the Polar Star Couloir on Mount Beluga in the [Kangiqtualuk Uqquqti](/Kangiqtualuk_Uqquqti) area is recognized in "Fifty Classic Ski Descents of North America" as a prime backcountry skiing challenge.

It's a place of extremes, of resilience, and of profound natural beauty. But don't expect me to wax poetic about it. It's simply a very large island.